@node "Intro" "Introduction"
 @{b}Introduction@{ub}
  BlackIRC is a new IRC(Internet Relay Chat)-Client for AmigaOS with special
  abilities. With BlackIRC it`s possible to take part in worldwide discussions
  over the net. Talk to the other end of the world with nearly no delay! But
  BlackIRC is more than just "yet another" client for IRC. It provides you with
  video conferencing features, so you can even see and watch people and people
  can see you. To also integrate PC-users, there is a special version of the
  video-client available. Communication gets more and more important and so
  you might want to join several channels at once, what could lead to you
  losing control and overview. This problem is also soluted with BlackIRC, as
  you can join several channels but only have one window where you can choose
  between the different channels. Of course you still have seperate message-
  windows for private messages to be able to chat with several people at once.
  But the main flood is taken away from you this way. If you also don`t like
  these disturbing advertisement messages, you can simply let them filter out
  by BlackIRC. And if you should not like some other people, filter them out,
  too. Besides its nice MUI-GUI, these are only some features that you`ll like
  about BlackIRC.
  
  Enjoy!
        Felix
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
 @{b}Features@{ub}
  (the most significant ones)
  À several channels in one window (*)
  À videoconferencing directly from within the IRC-Client (*)
  À IP-command making it possible to pass the IP of a user
    directly to a shell-command (*)
  À Join several channels automatically (*)
  À Small database for IRC-Servers
  À Own IdentD for you to be able to connect to most of the IRC-Servers
  À "Ignore content" against advertisment-messages (*)
  À All settings in one window (UserOP-switches, Watch, Ignore, Messages,
    MOTD, Transcript)
  À CTCP support
  À inbuilt CTCP-Flood detection and protection
  À CTCP server for easy defining of own CTCP commands (*)
  À inbuilt XDCC-Server
  À Event-Handler for maximal flexibility and reaction to events (*)
  À Support for colored text
  À Alias support
  À easy-to-use ARexx-port with many commands
  À DCC support
  À MUI-Userinterface
  À Textwrapping
  À up to 36 UserOP-switches

  @{b}(*) Features, that AFAIK no other client had before@{ub}
    
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
 @{b}Requirements@{ub}
  À AmigaOS 3.x (might also run on 2.x - not tested)
  À MUI 3.x
  À Busy.mcc
  À 2 MB Fast-RAM
@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Installation of BlackIRC"
 @{b}Installation@{ub}
  Simply drag BlackIRC to a drawer of your choice and copy the contents of
  Libs/ to Libs: Start BlackIRC with a double-click on its icon.

@endnode


@node "IRCBasic" "IRC Basics"
 @{b}IRC Basics@{ub}
  This chapter will give you short explanations to common IRC Terms
  and how IRC works.
  
  @{i}What is the IRC ?@{ui}
   IRC stands for "Internet Relay Chat" and is a global network of servers
   allowing people connected to them to communicate globally with each
   other. The IRC is organized in so called "Channels": Only users who
   "joined" the same channel get the messages other people posted to this
   channel. That allows many different discussions on many different
   topics without ending up in a chaos.
  
  @{i}IRC Terms@{ui}
   À @{b}Ban@{ub}
     If a user is banned by a channel-operator, he can`t join the channel
     any longer.

   À @{b}Bot@{ub}
     Short for "Robot". A bot is not a normal user but a program connected to
     an IRC server and acting like a user, but only very limited. Bots are often
     used to control channels.

   À @{b}Channel@{ub}
     The IRC is organized in so called "Channels": Only users who "joined"
     the same channel get the messages other people posted to this channel.
     That allows many different discussions on many different topics without
     ending up in a chaos.
  
   À @{b}Channel Operator@{ub}
     A user having control over a channel and though having more rights than
     others (e.g. kick or ban s.o)

   À @{b}CTCP@{ub}
     CTCP stands for "Client To Client Protocol" and allows clients to communicate
     with commands not standardized in the IRC-protocol. E.g. /version is using
     CTCP.

   À @{b}DCC@{ub}
     DCC stands for "Direct Client Connection" and allows clients to exchange files
     via a direct link.

   À @{b}IdentD@{ub}
     IdentD helps the server to identify you before allowing your in.

   À @{b}IRC@{ub}
     IRC stands for "Internet Relay Chat" and is a network of servers worldwide allowing
     users to meet and communicate.

   À @{b}Kick@{ub}
     A user being kicked leaves the channel without wanting so (well, in most cases :).
     Only channel ops can kick others.

   À MOTD
     The "Message Of The Day" sent to you at the beginning of a connection to an IRC-server.

   À @{b}Nick@{ub}
     Short for "Nickname". A nickname is a virtual name for you, that can be random and can
     be chosen by yourself.

   À @{b}OP@{ub}
     See "Channel Operator".

   À @{b}Topic@{ub}
     A line describing the content of the discussions going on on a channel.

   À @{b}Voice@{ub}
     If a channel is set the moderated flag, only people having voice can type
     to it.

  @{i}Shortcuts@{ui}
   À AFAIK
     As Far As I Know

   À AFK
     Away From Keyboard

   À BRB
     Be Right Back

   À BBL
     Be Back Later

   À CU
     = see you

   À IMHO
     In My Humble Opionion

   À LOL
     Laughing On Limmerick

   À L8R
     = later

   À ROTFL
     Rolling On The Floor Laughing

   À RTFM
     Read The F***ing Manual

   À RTM
     Read The Manual

   À WTF
     What The F***

   À WTH
     What The Heck

@endnode

@node "Connect" "Connecting to a server"
 @{b}Connecting@{ub}
  Connecting to IRC is quite easy with BlackIRC. Simply doubleclick on
  its icon on the Workbench to start it. Now the BlackIRC-window will
  pop up showing the About-part. Click on "@{"Servers" link "GUI_Servers"}" on the top
  bar. To set up BlackIRC properly, you have to enter your so called "nickname"
  that needn`t be your real name. Please don`t use spaces or other special signs for
  your nickname, as this might lead to problems. Try to use numbers and standard
  letters only. After that, enter your real name in the "Real name"-field. Ok, now
  we are ready to have a go and connect to the internet the first time: Select a server
  of your choice by clicking on its entry. Then click on "Connect" and BlackIRC will try
  to make a connection. This may take a while and BlackIRC`s GUI might block during
  connecting. Please note, that you have to be online in order to be able to connect
  to a server! If BlackIRC could connect successfully, you can now begin @{"Chatting" link "Chatting"}.

@endnode


@node "Chatting" "Chatting on the IRC"
 @{b}Chatting@{ub}
  After @{"connecting" link "Connect"} sucessfully, you can now begin to chat with other users
  on IRC. On the right is a list of the users currently on the same channel you activated.
  Every user with a "@" is a channel operator and people with "o" are people having voice.
  Say hello to the others by e.g typing "Hi all!" in the chat-line at the bottom of the window.
  The others might answer and you can begin chatting and making new friends all round the world.
  
  If you are not satisfied with chatting on one channel, enter "/join <your channel>" in the
  chat-line and BlackIRC will try to enter the channel and if successful, it will add the channels
  name to the list on the left of the window. You can now switch between the channels by clicking
  on the channels name.

@endnode

@node "GUI_Chat" "GUI: Chat-Window"
 @{b}The Chat-window@{ub}
  It`s BlackIRC`s aim to make the IRC as comfortable usable as possible and
  it therfore has a well designed Chat-Window-part. It consists of the following
  parts:

  À The major part of the GUI is dominated by three Listviews:
        À The @{b}channel-listview@{ub} at the left listing all channels currently
          joined. Simply click on the entry of a channel to switch to its display.

        À The @{b}chat-listview@{ub}  in the middle listing all incoming messages
          to the currently selected/joined channel.

        À The @{b}user-listview@{ub} at the right listing all users having joined
          the currently selected/joined channel.

  À Below the channel-listview is a "@{b}Part@{ub}"-button. If you click on it, the
    currently selected/joined channel will be left.

  À Above and below of the channel- and the chat-listview are two lines of buttons
        À @{b}Above@{ub} you can find
              À the @{b}channel-label@{ub} displaying the currently joined/selected
                channel

              À the @{b}channel-topic-line@{ub} containing the topic of the currently
                joined/selected channel. You can edit it in order to change the topic.

              À the @{b}six channel-mode-buttons@{ub}
                    À "@{b}T@{ub}opic protection" - only channel operators can change the topic
                      of the channel
                    À "@{b}N@{ub}o messages from outside the channel" - nobody not having joined
                      the channel may write messages to/into it.
                    À "@{b}S@{ub}ecret channel" - if set, the channel is invisible until it is
                      joined
                    À "@{b}I@{ub}nvite only channel" - if set, the channel may only be joined by
                      users being invited to it before.
                    À "@{b}P@{ub}rivate channel" - if set, the channel topic of the channel isn`t
                      visible in the global channel list
                    À "@{b}M@{ub}oderated channel" - if set, only users being either channel operators
                      or having voice, can write to the channel.

        À @{b}Below@{ub} you can find
              À your @{b}status-display@{ub} which is completly filled, if you are channel
                operator and half filled if you "only" have voice.
              À your @{b}nickname-label@{ub} containing your current nickname.
              À the @{b}chat-line@{ub}: Type the text you want to send to the channel, here.
              À the @{b}"Away"-button@{ub}: If you leave your AMIGA for a cup of coffee and
                you want all people messaging you to know that you currently are not sitting
                in front of it, click on it once and another time, when you are back.

  À Above and below the user-listview you can find some other buttons and displays
        À @{b}Above@{ub} you can find
              À the @{b}BlackIRC-logo@{ub} :)
              À the @{b}usercount-line@{ub} telling you the number of operators (Ops)
                and total number of users currently in your channel.

        À @{b}Below@{ub} you can find
              À the @{b}lag-meter@{ub} displaying you how long there was no message from
                the server.

              À the @{b}UserOP-buttons@{ub} that can be configured in the @{"UserOP-setup-part" link "GUI_UserOP"}.
                To use them click on a user in the user-listview and then click on one
                of the UserOP-buttons to perform an action on him/her. The UserOP-Switches
                are devided in three banks, each carrying 12 buttons. This enables you to
                sort your commands.
@endnode

@node "GUI_Servers" "GUI: Server"
 @{b}The Server-part@{ub}
  Here you do all the major settings for BlackIRC and needed for chatting.
  
  À @{b}Nickname@{ub}
    Enter your nickname here (e.g. DarkMan).
    
  À @{b}Realname@{ub}
    Enter your real name (e.g. John Smith) here.

  À @{b}Username@{ub}
    If the ENV-Var "USERNAME" doesn`t exist yet, BlackIRC will set it
    to the value entered here. You should enter the same name you entered
    in your TCP/IP-Stack, here.
    
  À @{b}Listview with all servers@{ub}
    Click on one of the servers to activate it and be able to edit it:
    À @{i}Server@{ui}
      The adress of the server, e.g. irc.uni-erlangen.de
      
    À @{i}Port@{ui}
      Port of the server, normally 6667
      
    À @{i}Password@{ui}
      Normally you can leave this field free, but if you need a password to enter
      a server, then place it here.
      
    À @{i}Comment@{ui}
      Small comment on the whole entry (e.g. DalNet)
      
    À @{i}Auto-join@{ui}
      Enter all channels you want BlackIRC to join automatically after a successful
      connection to the server, here. Seperate them with a commata (e.g. #BlackIRC, #amiga).
      
  À @{b}Connect@{ub}
    Connects you to the currently chosen server.
    
  À @{b}Co-connect@{ub}
    Starts another BlackIRC-task to connect to another server.
  
  À @{b}Disconnect@{ub}
    Disconnects from the server you are connected to.
    
  À @{b}New server-entry@{ub}
    Creates a new server-entry.
    
  À @{b}Delete server-entry@{ub}
    Deletes the currently chosen server-entry.
    
@endnode

