        >@{"Event-Handler " link "GUI_EventHandler"}
        >@{"Other settings" link "GUI_Otherset"}

@endnode

@node "GUI_Communication" "GUI: Setup/Communication"
 @{b}Communication@{ub}
   Here you can set the most important settings for communication via IRC:
   À @{b}Ignore@{ub}
     À @{i}Ignore contents@{ui}
       Some companies think, that the best way to promote their "sites" is
       to nerv the users on IRC with annoying advertisment messages. BlackIRC
       frees you from such stuff by allowing you to enter some keywords, BlackIRC
       does look for before opening a NEW private chat window. All keywords must
       be seperated by a commata, e.g
        free, trial
       ignores messages like (sarcastic examples :)
        Free homepage for only 50$/month .. visit http://...
        Free trial membership at `WeAreStupid` .. TODAY ONLY!! visit our sucking site..
       
       So you finally can chat with other people without being permanently disturbed
       by advertisement-messages.
       
     À @{i}Ignore user@{ui}
       If some users simply get on your nerves or bomb you with any messages, you can
       turn this off by entering the user`s nickname or IP-mask here. If you want to ignore
       several users, then seperate their names by a commata.
       Examples:
        billy!#?monopolsoft.com .. ignores nick "billy" on host #?monopolsoft.com
        #?monopolsoft#?         .. ignores any user whose nickname or host contains monopolsoft.
        sonic                   .. ignores any user whose nickname is sonic

   À @{b}Watch@{ub}
     À @{i}Watch user(s)@{ui}
       If you have some friends on IRC that you want to talk to, if they are there,
       you can enter some nicknames here (each seperated by a commata). Their status
       will be determined by clicking on @{i}Get status@{ui}.
@endnode

@node "GUI_Conference" "GUI: Setup/Conference"
 @{b}Conference@{ub}
   Here you can set the most important settings for conferences via BlackIRC:
   À @{b}Video@{ub}
     À @{i}Video-input@{ui}
       If you own a VLab for videoconferencing with BlackIRC, enter the input of your
       camera here.
              
     À @{i}Start AmVideoConfD@{ui}
       Launches the videoconferencing-daemon/server to enable others to see you.
       ATTENTION: Only press this button, if you own a vlab.library-compatible board.

   À @{b}Audio@{ub}
     This part of BlackIRC is still under construction :)
   
@endnode

@node "GUI_UserOP" "GUI: Setup/UserOP"
 @{b}UserOP-Switches@{ub}
   Here you can set the UserOP-switches available at the main chat-window.
   Add a UserOP-Switch with "New" and delete a UserOP-switch and its entry with
   "Delete". If you have added a new switch, you can enter its label in the field
   next to "Name" and its command at "Command". The UserOP-Switches all describe
   an action to be performed on a user. You may use several variables, that will
   be replaced with the correct strings:
    %n - your nickname
    %c - name of the channel currently joined/chosen
    %u - the nickname of the user you selected
   %ip - IP of the user you selected (only when used together with /IP-command)
@endnode

@node "GUI_Messages" "GUI: Setup/Messages"
 @{b}Messages@{ub}
   BlackIRC automatically sends messages to the server at special
   events. The messages can be changed here:
   À CTCP-Userinfo
     When getting a CTCP USERINFO, BlackIRC sends this string as
     reply.

   À KICK-reason
     If you kick someone off the channel, BlackIRC gives this
     string as a reason.

   À QUIT-messages
     When quitting BlackIRC and the server, BlackIRC sends this
     to the server.

   À Away-reason
     If you are marked as being away and someone sends a message to you,
     he automatically gets this string as answer.

   À CTCP-Flood-Message
     If someone attacks you by doing a CTCP Flood and BlackIRC detects it
     (depends on whether you have enabled "CTCP Flood Protection"), it also
     sends a message to the user who has attacked you. You can enter the
     message to be sent in this field.

@endnode

@node "GUI_CTCPServer" "GUI: Setup/CTCP Server"
 @{b}The CTCP Server@{ub}
   The CTCP Server is an invention of BlackIRC`s users and its programmer.
   It allows you to define certain actions for selfdefined CTCP-Commands.
   This enables you to offer advanced services over IRC and easy and transparent
   adding of features. E.g. reacting on a "GREETME"-CTCP-Request with an
   individual greeting message is very easy.

   Here are the explanations for the GUI of the CTCP Server:
   À CTCP Command
     Enter the name of your new CTCP-Command here.

   À Action-<Cycle>
     Here you can define the kind of (re)action of BlackIRC to
     a certain CTCP command. The following actions are currently
     available:
     - Text
       Send back the text in the parameter-field to the user who sent
       the request.

     - CLI
       Execute the CLI-command entered in the parameter-field.

     - ARexx
       Execute the ARexx-script entered in the parameter-field.
       Don`t forget to give the full pathname!

     - Sound
       Play the soundfile entered in the parameter-field via Datatypes.

     - DCC Send
       Send the file entered in the parameter-field via DCC.

     - Type
       Simulate an entry via a chatline.
       E.g.
       /msg %u Hello %u :)

     - Internal XDCC
       This allows you to map ANY CTCP-Command to the internal XDCC-
       routines. Normally, XDCC should be used. If you want to disable
       XDCC, simply remove the line with "Internal XDCC".

   À New
     Adds an entry to the CTCP Server

   À Delete
     Removes currently selected CTCP Server-entry

@endnode

@node "GUI_XDCC" "GUI: Setup/XDCC"
 @{b}XDCC@{ub}
   XDCC is a common standard for offering and sending files by remote
   requests. The user of your XDCC-offerings may request a list of all
   your files available and then choose to download or not. The files in
   BlackIRC are organized in slots. Why "slot" ? Well, BlackIRC also allows
   the user to enter more than one file for one number, just like a Zorro-
   slot offering you the ability to put one card in it and add several
   expansions to it.. ok, here are the explanations:

   À New
     Adds a new entry to the list of files

   À Delete
     Deletes currently selected entry.

   À Slot Number
     Enter the slot-number for your file here. You can give several
     files the same slotnumber in order to all send them to one user
     at once.

   À File
     The file for the slotnumber. You can also make use of the
     ASL-filerequester to choose files.

   Supported commands of the internal XDCC-"Server":
   À HELP
     Can be reached via /CTCP <user> XDCC HELP

   À SEND
     Can be reached via /CTCP <user> XDCC SEND <slotnumber>

   À LIST
     Can be reached via /CTCP <user> XDCC LIST

@endnode

@node "GUI_ALIASES" "GUI: Setup/Aliases"
 @{b}Aliases@{ub}
  Aliases enable you to shorten a lot of commands or connect them to
  an ARexx-script. So, basically, aliases are some kind of abreiviations.

  Find "Alias" to contain the shortened command and "Extended" to contain
  the extended command.
  E.g.
  /m
  and
  /msg %p

  The following variables are supported:
   %p All parameters passed to the command
   %u The user currently selected in the userlist

@endnode

@node "GUI_Eventhandler" "GUI: Setup/Event-Handler"
 @{b}The Event-Handler@{ub}
  Yet another invention contained in BlackIRC, it is enabling you to
  connect operations to certain events. E.g. if someone with a certain nickname
  joins a channel, you can op him/her, play a sound, etc.

  The first cycle-gadget describes one of the following basic events:
  À Start
    Occurs when BlackIRC is started.

  À Quit
    Occurs when BlackIRC quits.

  À CTCP-Cmd
    If ANY CTCP-command is received, this event occurs.

  À Connect
    Occurs, when BlackIRC just got connected.

  À Disconnect
    Occurs, when BlackIRC is disconnecting.

  À Receive
    If a line was received, this event occurs.
    Quite useful together with "Highlight".

  À Join
    If anyone joins the channel, this event occurs.

  À Hotkey
    If F1, F2 ... F10 was pressed, this event occurs.
    Can only be used together with "Insert".

  The second cycle-gadget and the parameter-field describe the
  action to take. These actions are available:
  À CLI
    Execute specified CLI-command.

  À ARexx
    Execute specified ARexx-command.

  À Sound
    Play specified Soundfile via Datatypes.

  À Highlight
    Highlight the current line, if it matches the pattern
    put into "Parameter". E.g.
     Hello world!!
    matches
     #?Hello#?
    and is highlighted.

  À Op
    Op the user who is responsible for an action, if his/her
    nickname is matching a pattern. You can use Amiga-Wildcards
    for discribing a user`s nickname.

  À DeOp
    DeOp the user who is responsible for an action, if his/her
    nickname is matching a pattern. You can use Amiga-Wildcards
    for discribing a user`s nickname.

  À Kick
    Kick the user who is responsible for an action, if his/her
    nickname is matching a pattern. You can use Amiga-Wildcards
    for discribing a user`s nickname.

  À Insert
    Can only be used together with "Hotkey" and inserts a text at
    a the current cursor-position in the chatline. The parameter
    has to have a special format:
    <hotkey-num>\<action>

    e.g. if F5 is pressed and you want to insert "/msg <currently selected user>", enter:
    5\/msg %u

  The "New" and "Delete"-buttons add or remove an entry from the list.
@endnode

@node "GUI_Otherset" "GUI: Setup/Other Settings"
 @{b}Othersettings@{ub}
   All settings that don`t fit into the other categories can be changed
   here. These are:
   À Auto Rejoin after a kick
     If you were kicked off a channel and want to stay tuned nevertheless,
     enable this checkbox and BlackIRC will automatically rejoin the channel
     you were kicked from.

   À Sort nicknames in alphabetical order
     BlackIRC offers you the ability to sort the nicknames displayed in the
     lister in alphabetical order. If you prefer this type of displaying the
     nicknames, enable this option. Please note, that this can slow down BlackIRC
     a lot if you are on a channel with many users and many users joining and leaving!

   À Skip MOTD
     If your AMIGA is very slow at scrooling and it takes a half eternity
     to reach the end of the MOTD, then active this to skip viewing of
     the "Message Of the Day" (MOTD).

   À CTCP Flood Protection
     What is a CTCP Flood you might ask now. Well, e.g. if a user pings
     you as frequent as possible and therefore it`s impossible for you
     to read anything because everything is scrolling by so fast, you have
     a problem. BlackIRC solves it :) Enable this switch and BlackIRC will
     detect any CTCP Flood and autoignore the user who did it.

   À Transcript to file
     It sometimes is very important to transcript an IRC conference to a
     file. This can be done by entering the filename of the transcript-
     file here. If the field is empty, BlackIRC won`t do any transcript.

   À MUI Settings
     Click on this button to get to the MUI settings of the client.

@endnode

@node "Commands" "Commands"
 @{b}Commands@{ub}
  BlackIRC supports the following IRC commands INTERNALLY (the rest is directly
  passed to the server):
   @{"/nick" link "Comm" 0}
   @{"/msg" link "Comm" 4}
   @{"/me" link "Comm" 8}
   @{"/describe" link "Comm" 12}
   @{"/join" link "Comm" 14}
   @{"/kick" link "Comm" 18}
   @{"/op" link "Comm" 22}
   @{"/deop" link "Comm" 27}
   @{"/voice" link "Comm" 32}
   @{"/devoice" link "Comm" 36}
   @{"/topic" link "Comm" 40}
   @{"/clear" link "Comm" 43}
   @{"/ctcp" link "Comm" 46}
   @{"/ban" link "Comm" 49}
   @{"/bandel" link "Comm" 52}
   @{"/banlist" link "Comm" 55}
   @{"/query" link "Comm" 58}
   @{"/ip" link "Comm" 61}
   @{"/ignore" link "Comm" 66}
   @{"/ignorecontent" link "Comm" 69}
   @{"/watch" link "Comm" 75}
   @{"/quit" link "Comm" 75}
   @{"/quote" link "Comm" 78}
   @{"/raw" link "Comm" 78}
   @{"/rexx" link Comm" 200}
   @{"/sendfile" link "Comm" 83}
   @{"/sound" link "Comm" 86}

@endnode

@node "Comm" "Commands - Overview"
 @{b}Overview over all internal commands of BlackIRC@{ub}

   @{b}/nick <nickname>@{ub}
    Changes your nickname to <nickname>.
    E.g. /nick DarkMan

   @{b}/msg  <to nick> <message> @{ub}
    Sends a private message <message> to <to nick>.
    E.g. /msg DarkMan Hi!

   @{b}/me <action>@{ub}
    Sends the action <action> to the currently active channel.
    E.g. /me is astonished!

   @{b}/describe <to nick> <describe>@{ub}
    Describes <describe> to <to nick>.
    E.g. /describe DarkMan I`m online via an AMIGA .. and they`re cool!

   @{b}/join <channel>@{ub}
    Joins <channel>.
    E.g. /join #BlackIRC

   @{b}/kick <nick> <kick reason>@{ub}
    Kicks <nick> because of the reason <kick reason>.
    E.g. /kick Olli Wrong IRC-client :)

   @{b}/op <user>@{ub}
    If you are a channel operator and want to give this status to another
    user, then use this command. It ops the user <user>.
    E.g. /op DarkMan

   @{b}/deop <user>@{ub}
    If you are a channel operator and want to take the operator-status
    from another user, then use this command.
    E.g. /deop Lamer

   @{b}/voice <nick>@{ub}
    Gives "voice" to the user <nick>.
    E.g. /voice DarkMan

   @{b}/devoice <nick>@{ub}
    Takes "voice" from the user <nick>.
    E.g. /devoice DarkMan

   @{b}/topic <channel> <new topic>@{ub}
    Changes the topic of <channel> to <new topic>.

   @{b}/clear@{ub}
    Clears the buffer content of the currently joined channel.

   @{b}/ctcp <to user> <CTCP command>@{ub}
    Sends the CTCP-command <CTCP command> to <to user>.

   @{b}/ban <user>@{ub}
    Bans the user <user> from the currently joined channel.

   @{b}/bandel <user>@{ub}
    Deletes the ban on user <user> for the currently joined channel.

   @{b}/banlist [<channel>]@{ub}
    Lists the bans for the currently joined channel.

   @{b}/query <user>@{ub}
    Opens a private chat-window to the user <user>.

   @{b}/ip <user> <command>@{ub}
    This is the special IP-command of BlackIRC that allows you to pass
    the IP of a user to a shell-command (such as ping). Simply put %ip
    there, where the command needs the address.

   @{b}/ignore <user>@{ub}
    Adds the user <user> to the list of ignored users.

   @{b}/ignorecontent <word>@{ub}
    Adds the word <word> to the list of ignored words and contents. The
    first private message from another user containing one of these words
    will be ignored.

   @{b}/watch <user>@{ub}
    Adds the user <user> to the list of users to watch.

   @{b}/quit <reason>@{ub}
    Quits and closes current IRC-connection with the reason <reason>.

   @{b}/quote <raw-text>@{ub}
   @{b}/raw <raw-text>@{ub}
    Sends the raw-text <raw-text> to the server you are currently connected
    to.

   @{b}/sendfile <user>@{ub}
    Sends a file (you can choose using an ASL-requester) to the user <user>.

   @{b}/sound <sound-file>@{ub}
    Sends a CTCP-sound-request to the currently joined channel.

   @{b}/rexx <Rexx-script>@{ub}
    Executes the Rexx-Script <Rexx-script> in the subdirectory "Rexx/" of
    BlackIRC. If the Rexx-script`s extension is ".birx", you needn`t add this,
    as RexxMast (which has to be started before ;-) adds this automatically.

@endnode

